      <exercises>
      <title>Factoring Trinomials with Leading Coefficients of 1</title>

      <exercise>
        <title>Explanation and examples</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Factoring a trinomial of form <m>x^2+bx+c</m>, where <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are integers, is essentially the reversal of a FOIL process.  For this reason, we can develop a strategy by investigating a FOIL expansion.  Let's expand <m>(x+4)(x+6)</m>.                   
                   </p>
                   <md>
                    <mrow>(x+4)(x+6)\amp=x^2+6x+4x+24</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=x^2+10x+24</mrow>
                  </md>
                  <p>
                    Let's observe that the linear coefficient, <m>10</m>, is the sum of <m>4</m> and <m>6</m> whereas the constant term, <m>24</m>, is the product of <m>4</m> and <m>6</m>.  Since we expanded <m>(x+4)(x+6)</m>, we can infer that finding the constants in a factorization of trinomials of form <m>x^2+bx+c</m> is dependent upon determining two numbers that sum to <m>b</m> and multiply to <m>c</m>.
                  </p>
                    From the factor pairs and sums shown in <xref ref="table-trinomial-1">Table</xref>, we can infer the following factorizations. 
                  <p>

                  </p>
                  <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                    <md>
                      <mrow>x^2+7x+6\amp=(x+1)(x+6)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x^2+5x+6\amp=(x+2)(x+3)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x^2-7x+6\amp=(x-1)(x-6)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x^2-5x+6\amp=(x-2)(x-3)</mrow>
                    </md> 
                    </p>
                    

                    <table xml:id="table-trinomial-1">
                      <caption>Factor pairs of <m>6</m></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line>factors</line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line>sum</line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>1,6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>2,3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>-1,-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>-2,-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-5</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                    <p>
                      Just as noteworthy, since the factor pairs shown in <xref ref="table-trinomial-1">Table</xref> form an exhaustive list, we cannot factor any trinomial of form <m>x^2+bx+6</m> where b is not one of the four numbers shown in the sum column.  Such trinomials are said to be prime.  For example, <m>x^2+3x+6</m> is prime.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                    Let's factor <m>x^2-8x+15</m>.  Our first task is to determine a factor pair that multiplies to <m>15</m> and adds to <m>-8</m>.  Since the product is positive and the sum is negative, we are searching for two negative numbers.  The pair that works is <m>-3</m> and <m>-5</m>.  This gives us:
                    <me>x^2-8x+15=(x-3)(x-5)</me>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Now let's factor <m>w^2-4w-12</m>.  Since our factor pair needs to multiply to a negative value <m>(-12)</m>, one the numbers in the pair must be positive and the other negative.  Let's note that <m>6</m> and <m>2</m> multiply to 12 and have a difference of <m>4</m>.  This can be helpful in determining that the factor pair that multiplies to <m>-12</m> and adds to <m>-4</m> is <m>-6</m> and <m>2</m>.  This gives us <me>w^2-4w-12=(w-6)(w+2)</me>. 
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                      We also could have written the factorization in the reverse order: <me>w^2-4w-12=(w+2)(w-6)</me>.
                    </p>
                 </statement>
                </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Practice exercises with detailed solutions</title>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Factor each trinomial.  Check your answer by expanding the factorization.  If the trinomial cannot be factored, state that it is prime.
                    <ol cols="2">
                      <li><m>x^2+6x+5</m></li>
                      <li><m>t^2-6t+8</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+8x+4</m></li>
                      <li><m>y^2-14y-32</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+6x-20</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+15x-100</m></li>
                      <li><m>w^2-18w+45</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+21x+80</m></li>
                      <li><m>b^2-9b-400</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  <p></p></p>
                    
                  
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                     <ol>
                      <li><m>x^2+6x+5=(x+2)(x+3)</m></li>
                      <li><m>t^2-6t+8=(t-2)(t-4)</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+8x+4</m> is prime.</li>
                      <li><m>y^2-14y-32=(y-16)(y+2)</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+6x-20</m> is prime.</li>
                      <li><m>x^2+15x-100=(x+20)(x-5)</m></li>
                      <li><m>w^2-18w+45=(w-15)(w-3)</m></li>
                      <li><m>x^2+21x+80</m> is prime</li>
                      <li><m>b^2-9b-400=(b-25)(b+16)</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </p>
                  </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Question bank with short answers</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Factor each trinomial.
              <ol>
                <li><m>x^2-10x-24</m></li>
                <li><m>x^2+11x+30</m></li>
                <li><m>y^2-12y+36</m></li>
                <li><m>w^2+12w+24</m></li>
